{
  "Duchenne muscular dystrophy is caused by:": "",
  "Muscle overuse from excessive exercise": "",
  "A bacterial infection": "",
  "A vitamin deficiency": "",
  "A genetic mutation in the dystrophin gene (X-linked recessive)": "",
  "Duchenne muscular dystrophy is caused by mutations in the DMD gene on the X chromosome that lead to the absence of dystrophin, a critical protein that anchors the muscle fiber's cytoskeleton to the extracellular matrix, resulting in progressive muscle degeneration.": "",
  "Myasthenia gravis primarily affects the:": "",
  "The intestinal smooth muscle": "",
  "Bones and joints": "",
  "The brain's motor cortex": "",
  "Neuromuscular junction, where autoantibodies destroy ACh receptors": "",
  "Myasthenia gravis is an autoimmune disorder in which the immune system produces antibodies that attack and destroy nicotinic acetylcholine receptors at the neuromuscular junction, reducing the number of available receptors and causing progressive muscle weakness.": "",
  "Fibromyalgia is characterized by:": "",
  "Bone fractures throughout the body": "",
  "Visible muscle wasting and tissue destruction": "",
  "Chronic widespread musculoskeletal pain and fatigue without identifiable tissue damage": "",
  "Sudden acute muscle rupture": "",
  "Fibromyalgia is a chronic condition characterized by widespread musculoskeletal pain, fatigue, sleep disturbances, and cognitive difficulties, with no identifiable structural tissue damage on examination or imaging, thought to involve abnormal central pain processing.": "",
  "A muscle strain involves damage to:": "",
  "Overstretched or torn muscle fibers and/or tendons": "",
  "A crack or break in the periosteum and bone matrix": "",
  "An overstretched or torn ligament connecting bones": "",
  "A displacement of bones from their normal joint alignment": "",
  "A muscle strain is an injury to muscle fibers or their associated tendons caused by overstretching or excessive force, ranging from mild microscopic fiber damage (Grade I) to complete rupture (Grade III) of the muscle-tendon unit.": "",
  "Duchenne muscular dystrophy primarily affects:": "",
  "Adult men and women equally": "",
  "Only newborn females": "",
  "Boys, because it is X-linked recessive": "",
  "Elderly women": "",
  "Because Duchenne MD is X-linked recessive, males (who have only one X chromosome) are predominantly affected, while females typically serve as carriers with two X chromosomes providing a backup copy of the dystrophin gene.": "",
  "Rhabdomyolysis can lead to which serious complication?": "",
  "Stronger bones": "",
  "Improved athletic performance": "",
  "No significant complications": "",
  "Acute kidney failure due to myoglobin release into the bloodstream": "",
  "When muscle fibers are severely damaged and break down (rhabdomyolysis), large quantities of myoglobin are released into the bloodstream; this protein can precipitate in and clog the renal tubules, leading to acute kidney injury or failure.": "",
  "Tetanus (the disease) is caused by a toxin from which organism?": "",
  "Streptococcus pyogenes": "",
  "Escherichia coli": "",
  "Clostridium tetani": "",
  "Staphylococcus aureus": "",
  "Tetanus is caused by the neurotoxin tetanospasmin produced by the anaerobic bacterium Clostridium tetani, which blocks inhibitory neurotransmitter release in the spinal cord, resulting in uncontrolled muscle contraction and spasms (lockjaw).": "",
  "DOMS (Delayed Onset Muscle Soreness) typically occurs:": "",
  "24-72 hours after unaccustomed or intense exercise": "",
  "During exercise": "",
  "Immediately and resolves within minutes": "",
  "Only in professional athletes": "",
  "DOMS is delayed-onset muscle soreness that typically peaks 24-72 hours after exercise, especially eccentric exercise, and is caused by microscopic damage to muscle fibers that triggers an inflammatory repair response.": "",
  "Botulinum toxin (Botox) works by:": "",
  "Stimulating acetylcholine release for stronger contractions": "",
  "Blocking ACh release at the neuromuscular junction, causing localized muscle paralysis": "",
  "Increasing calcium release from the sarcoplasmic reticulum": "",
  "Strengthening muscle fibers through protein synthesis": "",
  "Botulinum toxin blocks the release of acetylcholine from the presynaptic terminal at the NMJ by cleaving SNARE proteins required for vesicle fusion, causing temporary, localized muscle paralysis used therapeutically for spasticity, dystonia, and cosmetically for wrinkle reduction.": "",
  "The RICE protocol for acute muscle injuries stands for:": "",
  "Resist, Inflate, Compress, Extend": "",
  "Run, Ice, Contract, Elevate": "",
  "Rehab, Inject, Cool, Exercise": "",
  "Rest, Ice, Compression, Elevation": "",
  "RICE (Rest, Ice, Compression, Elevation) is the standard first-aid protocol for acute musculoskeletal injuries that helps reduce swelling, inflammation, and pain in the initial 48-72 hours after injury.": "",
  "What is muscular dystrophy?": "",
  "A condition where muscles grow too large from overuse": "",
  "A temporary muscle cramp caused by dehydration": "",
  "An infection of the muscle tissue by bacteria": "",
  "A group of inherited genetic diseases characterized by progressive muscle weakness and degeneration due to defective structural proteins": "",
  "Muscular dystrophy encompasses a group of more than 30 inherited genetic disorders in which mutations in genes encoding structural muscle proteins (like dystrophin) lead to progressive skeletal muscle weakness, degeneration, and replacement with fibrotic and fatty tissue.": "",
  "What is atrophy in the context of muscular disorders?": "",
  "A decrease in muscle size and strength resulting from disuse, denervation, aging, or disease": "",
  "An increase in muscle size from exercise": "",
  "The normal resting tone of a healthy muscle": "",
  "The formation of new muscle fibers during recovery": "",
  "Atrophy is the wasting or reduction in muscle size that occurs when muscle fibers shrink due to decreased protein synthesis and increased protein degradation, caused by factors such as prolonged immobilization, nerve damage, aging (sarcopenia), or chronic disease.": "",
  "What is hypertrophy?": "",
  "The accumulation of fat within muscle tissue": "",
  "An increase in muscle size caused by enlargement of individual muscle fibers, typically from resistance training": "",
  "The multiplication of muscle cells to create new fibers": "",
  "The shrinking of muscle fibers due to inactivity": "",
  "Hypertrophy is the increase in skeletal muscle size that results from enlargement of existing muscle fibers (not creation of new ones) through increased synthesis of myofilaments and myofibrils, typically stimulated by resistance training and adequate nutrition.": "",
  "What is compartment syndrome?": "",
  "A fracture that damages the bone marrow compartment, releasing fat globules into the bloodstream that can cause a systemic fat embolism": "",
  "A dangerous condition where increased pressure within a closed muscle compartment compresses blood vessels and nerves, cutting off blood flow": "",
  "An infection within the joint space that spreads to surrounding tissues, causing inflammation and eventual destruction of the articular cartilage": "",
  "A benign and self-limiting condition of mild muscle swelling that resolves spontaneously without any medical or surgical intervention needed": "",
  "Compartment syndrome occurs when swelling or bleeding within a closed fascial compartment raises the pressure to a level that compromises blood flow and nerve function, leading to ischemia and potential permanent tissue damage if not treated with emergency fasciotomy.": "",
  "What is dystrophin?": "",
  "A structural protein that connects the muscle fiber's cytoskeleton to the extracellular matrix, providing mechanical stability during contraction": "",
  "An enzyme that breaks down lactic acid in muscles": "",
  "A neurotransmitter released at the neuromuscular junction": "",
  "A contractile protein that generates the power stroke": "",
  "Dystrophin is a large, rod-shaped cytoskeletal protein that forms a crucial link between the intracellular actin cytoskeleton and the extracellular matrix through the dystrophin-associated glycoprotein complex, protecting the sarcolemma from mechanical stress during contraction; its absence causes Duchenne muscular dystrophy.": "",
  "What does 'autoimmune disorder' mean in the context of myasthenia gravis?": "",
  "A condition in which the body's immune system mistakenly attacks its own tissues, in this case destroying ACh receptors at the NMJ": "",
  "An infection by a virus that attacks the muscles": "",
  "A genetic mutation that prevents immune cells from forming": "",
  "A disorder caused by excessive exercise damaging the immune system": "",
  "An autoimmune disorder occurs when the immune system loses self-tolerance and generates antibodies against the body's own tissues; in myasthenia gravis, autoantibodies target and destroy nicotinic ACh receptors on the motor end plate, progressively reducing neuromuscular transmission.": "",
  "What does 'rhabdomyolysis' mean?": "",
  "An inflammation of the joints surrounding muscles": "",
  "The rapid breakdown (lysis) of damaged skeletal muscle (rhabdomyo-) releasing intracellular contents into the bloodstream": "",
  "The growth of smooth muscle in the blood vessels": "",
  "The normal breakdown and rebuilding of muscle during exercise": "",
  "Rhabdomyolysis literally means 'dissolution of striped (skeletal) muscle' and refers to the pathological destruction of muscle cells that releases potentially harmful intracellular contents (myoglobin, potassium, creatine kinase) into the blood, which can cause kidney failure and cardiac arrhythmias.": "",
  "What is a muscle spasm?": "",
  "The normal resting tone maintained by motor neurons": "",
  "A sudden, involuntary, sustained contraction of a muscle or group of muscles that is often painful": "",
  "Voluntary contraction performed during exercise": "",
  "A complete tear of a muscle tendon": "",
  "A muscle spasm (or cramp) is an involuntary, sustained, and often painful contraction that occurs without conscious control, commonly caused by electrolyte imbalances, dehydration, muscle fatigue, or nerve irritation.": "",
  "What does 'demyelination' mean in the context of multiple sclerosis and muscle weakness?": "",
  "The destruction of the myelin sheath insulating nerve fibers, which slows or blocks nerve impulse transmission to muscles": "",
  "The growth of new nerve fibers to replace damaged ones": "",
  "The strengthening of the nerve coating to improve signal speed": "",
  "The increase in muscle fiber size due to nerve stimulation": "",
  "Demyelination is the loss or destruction of the myelin sheath that normally insulates nerve fibers and speeds up signal conduction; in multiple sclerosis, the immune system attacks myelin on central nervous system neurons, slowing or blocking motor signals and causing muscle weakness, spasticity, and coordination problems.": "",
  "What does 'sprain' mean, and how does it differ from a strain?": "",
  "A sprain and a strain are the same injury affecting muscles": "",
  "A sprain is a bone fracture and a strain is a nerve injury": "",
  "A sprain affects tendons and a strain affects ligaments": "",
  "A sprain is an injury to a ligament (connecting bone to bone), while a strain is an injury to a muscle or tendon (connecting muscle to bone)": "",
  "A sprain involves the stretching or tearing of a ligament (the fibrous connective tissue connecting bones at a joint), such as an ankle sprain, while a strain involves the stretching or tearing of a muscle or its tendon, such as a hamstring strain.": "",
  "A 5-year-old boy is brought to the pediatrician because his parents notice he uses his hands to 'walk up' his legs when standing from the floor (Gowers' sign). Genetic testing reveals an absence of dystrophin. What diagnosis should the physician suspect, and why does the child display this maneuver?": "",
  "A simple muscle strain that will heal in a few weeks": "",
  "Myasthenia gravis; the child lacks ACh receptors at the NMJ": "",
  "Duchenne muscular dystrophy; without dystrophin, proximal muscles (especially hip and thigh extensors) weaken, forcing the child to use arm support to compensate": "",
  "Fibromyalgia; the child is experiencing chronic pain without tissue damage": "",
  "Gowers' sign is a classic clinical indicator of Duchenne muscular dystrophy where the child uses the arms to 'climb up' the body when rising from the floor because the proximal hip and thigh muscles are severely weakened due to absence of dystrophin, which normally protects muscle fibers from contraction-induced damage.": "",
  "A 35-year-old woman reports that her eyelids droop progressively throughout the day and she has difficulty chewing by dinnertime, but symptoms improve after a night's rest. A neurologist suspects myasthenia gravis. Why do symptoms worsen with repeated use and improve with rest?": "",
  "Her bones are weakening throughout the day from osteoporosis": "",
  "With repeated nerve stimulation, the already-reduced ACh receptors become further depleted of available binding sites, but rest allows some recovery of neuromuscular transmission": "",
  "Her muscles are being destroyed by a toxin that accumulates during the day": "",
  "She has a muscle strain that worsens with movement": "",
  "In myasthenia gravis, autoantibodies have destroyed a significant portion of ACh receptors; with repeated stimulation, the limited remaining receptors become saturated and fewer end-plate potentials reach threshold, causing progressive weakness; rest allows ACh to accumulate and partial recovery of receptor availability.": "",
  "A college student starts an intense new workout program and develops severe muscle pain, swelling, and dark cola-colored urine 48 hours later. The emergency physician orders blood tests showing elevated creatine kinase and myoglobin. What condition does the student most likely have, and why is it dangerous?": "",
  "Rhabdomyolysis, which is dangerous because released myoglobin can clog renal tubules and cause acute kidney failure": "",
  "Normal DOMS that requires no treatment": "",
  "A simple muscle strain requiring only rest and ice": "",
  "Fibromyalgia triggered by exercise": "",
  "Dark urine (myoglobinuria), severe muscle pain, and markedly elevated creatine kinase are hallmarks of rhabdomyolysis, where extensive muscle breakdown releases myoglobin into the blood; myoglobin precipitates in renal tubules, and without aggressive IV fluid therapy, acute kidney failure can develop rapidly.": "",
  "A soldier steps on a rusty nail in a muddy field and does not receive proper wound care. Two weeks later, he develops jaw stiffness (lockjaw) and generalized muscle spasms. The field medic recognizes tetanus. How does the tetanus toxin cause these sustained muscle contractions?": "",
  "The toxin destroys the sarcoplasmic reticulum, causing calcium to flood the muscle": "",
  "The toxin directly stimulates muscle fibers to contract without any nerve involvement": "",
  "The toxin increases acetylcholinesterase activity, causing muscle relaxation": "",
  "The toxin blocks inhibitory neurotransmitter release (GABA and glycine) in the spinal cord, leaving motor neurons unchecked and causing sustained muscle contraction": "",
  "Tetanospasmin from Clostridium tetani travels retrogradely along motor neurons to the spinal cord, where it blocks the release of inhibitory neurotransmitters (GABA and glycine) from Renshaw cells and inhibitory interneurons, resulting in unopposed motor neuron firing and sustained, painful muscle spasms.": "",
  "A nurse is caring for an ICU patient who develops sudden, severe pain and swelling in his right lower leg after a tibial fracture was casted. The limb appears tense, and the patient reports numbness in the foot. The surgeon is urgently called. What is the likely diagnosis, and why is emergency surgery needed?": "",
  "Fibromyalgia triggered by the traumatic injury; the widespread muscle pain and tenderness are characteristic of this chronic pain condition and should be managed with analgesics and physical therapy": "",
  "Acute compartment syndrome; the rising pressure within the fascial compartment is compressing blood vessels and nerves, and without emergency fasciotomy, the tissue will die from ischemia": "",
  "Normal post-fracture swelling that requires only ice and elevation; the pain and tightness are expected after a tibia fracture and will resolve with standard conservative management over several days": "",
  "A deep venous thrombosis forming at the fracture site that is compressing the surrounding tissues; this can be treated with anticoagulant medication alone without any surgical intervention required": "",
  "Acute compartment syndrome is a surgical emergency where swelling within a rigid fascial compartment raises pressure above capillary perfusion pressure, cutting off blood flow to muscles and nerves; without fasciotomy (surgical opening of the compartment) within 6 hours, irreversible muscle necrosis and nerve damage occur.": "",
  "A dermatologist is using Botox injections to treat a patient with chronic migraines. The patient asks how a toxin can be a medicine. Based on knowledge of muscular disorders, what is the therapeutic mechanism of Botox?": "",
  "Botox increases blood flow to the brain by stimulating smooth muscle": "",
  "Botox blocks ACh release at the NMJ in very small, targeted doses, temporarily relaxing overactive muscles and reducing the muscle tension that triggers migraines": "",
  "Botox kills the bacteria that cause migraines": "",
  "Botox strengthens the muscles around the head to prevent headaches": "",
  "Therapeutic Botox uses tiny, precisely targeted doses of botulinum toxin to block ACh release at selected neuromuscular junctions, causing localized, temporary muscle paralysis that reduces the excessive muscle tension contributing to chronic migraines, cervical dystonia, and spasticity.": "",
  "A physical therapist is treating a patient with multiple sclerosis (MS) who is experiencing increasing weakness and spasticity in her legs. The patient asks why her muscles are getting weaker even though the disease affects nerves, not muscles. What is the best explanation?": "",
  "MS destroys the myelin sheath on central nervous system motor neurons, impairing nerve signal transmission to muscles and causing weakness and spasticity even though the muscles themselves are initially healthy": "",
  "MS is actually a primary muscle disease that has been historically misclassified as a neurological condition; the muscle fibers themselves undergo autoimmune destruction, leading to progressive loss of contractile tissue": "",
  "MS directly destroys the skeletal muscle fibers through an autoimmune attack on the sarcolemma, causing progressive loss of contractile protein and eventual dissolution of the affected myofibrils": "",
  "MS causes demineralization and weakening of the bones that serve as muscle attachment sites, reducing the mechanical leverage available to muscles and making them appear functionally weak": "",
  "In MS, the autoimmune destruction of myelin in the central nervous system slows or blocks motor signals traveling from the brain and spinal cord to skeletal muscles; although the muscles themselves are initially structurally normal, impaired innervation causes weakness, and damaged inhibitory pathways lead to spasticity.": "",
  "An elderly patient has been hospitalized for pneumonia and confined to bed for 3 weeks. Upon discharge, she is unable to walk unassisted. Her doctor explains that her leg muscles have atrophied. The patient asks if the muscle loss is permanent. What is the most accurate response?": "",
  "Disuse atrophy is generally reversible with progressive exercise and physical therapy, as the muscle fibers can regrow and strengthen with appropriate stimulation": "",
  "Yes, disuse atrophy is always permanent and irreversible": "",
  "Surgery is the only way to restore atrophied muscles": "",
  "The muscles were not actually lost; they just shrank temporarily and will return to normal size immediately": "",
  "Disuse atrophy is generally reversible because the muscle fibers shrink but are not destroyed; with progressive resistance exercise and physical therapy, protein synthesis increases, myofibrils are rebuilt, and muscle size and strength can be largely restored, though recovery may take longer in elderly patients.": "",
  "A weekend warrior participates in an unusually intense hiking trip after months of inactivity. Two days later, he can barely walk down stairs due to severe quadriceps soreness. Based on understanding of DOMS, what caused this delayed soreness and what type of contraction during hiking likely contributed most?": "",
  "Lactic acid buildup during the hike caused permanent muscle damage": "",
  "A bacterial infection entered the muscles during the hike": "",
  "The concentric contractions during uphill climbing caused all of the soreness": "",
  "Eccentric contractions of the quadriceps during downhill sections caused microscopic muscle fiber damage and an inflammatory repair response that peaks 24-72 hours later": "",
  "DOMS is primarily caused by eccentric contractions (which occur extensively during downhill walking when the quadriceps lengthens under load to control knee flexion), producing microscopic tears in muscle fibers and Z-line disruption, triggering an inflammatory response that causes pain peaking 24-72 hours post-exercise.": "",
  "A pediatric neurologist is counseling the mother of a boy newly diagnosed with Duchenne muscular dystrophy. The mother, who has no symptoms, asks why she is not affected by the disease if she carries the same mutation. What genetic explanation should the neurologist provide?": "",
  "DMD only affects children under age 10 and adults are immune": "",
  "The mother does not actually carry the mutation; it arose spontaneously in the child": "",
  "The disease is caused by environmental factors, not genetics": "",
  "As a female carrier, the mother has two X chromosomes; her normal X chromosome produces enough dystrophin to compensate for the mutated one, while her son has only one X chromosome with no backup": "",
  "Duchenne MD is X-linked recessive; female carriers have two X chromosomes, and the normal copy on one X produces sufficient dystrophin through random X-inactivation to maintain muscle function, while males have only one X chromosome and therefore express the full disease phenotype when the dystrophin gene is mutated.": ""
}